{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b9f8685-eb1b-4d2a-a0e0-70ad1c7356ba","content":"Here's the mapping from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to the platform runner. You'll also need these NuGet packages in the test project:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\nAnd enable the runner in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n| VSTest flag | Platform equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\nThe `--filter` stays before `--` since `dotnet test` translates it for you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"140a942b-58a8-416e-b9ae-3ad646d29716","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure - I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me break down their current command and map each part to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalent:\n\n1. `dotnet test` → `dotnet test` (still works, but the test project needs to opt in to Microsoft.Testing.Platform)\n2. `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` → `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` (filter syntax changes slightly; in Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the filter is passed differently)\n\n\n3. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in TRX report)\n4. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` or use Microsoft.CodeCoverage with `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n5. `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump` (Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalent)\n6. `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n7. `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nI need to clarify the distinction between running through `dotnet test` versus directly executing the test binary, since Microsoft.Testing.Platform handles these differently. When using `dotnet test`, some arguments pass through but the native flags differ—for instance, `--filter` still works though property names like `Category` map to `TestCategory` in certain frameworks. The TRX logger requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package to use `--report-trx`, code coverage needs `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` for the `--coverage` flags, and crash dumps require another extension package.\n\nWhen running via `dotnet test`, I pass Microsoft.Testing.Platform arguments after `--`, and in .NET 9+ there's native integration that understands some of these flags directly. For .NET 8, I need to set the project property to enable the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner. I need to specify the required NuGet packages for the coverage, crash dump, hang dump, and trx report extensions to make this work properly.","outputTokens":1455,"requestId":"1BD7:FFF68:2096E3C:23FD095:6A03CEAC"},"id":"2bcd4224-b975-44ef-bbcc-dfe45c973eb3","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:07:17.756Z","parentId":"fabe9034-214d-4a64-b3d0-3efa8b3633a3"}
